        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.audit.declareAsInterface.comment=Great idea, but there will always be at least some exceptions, and we don't want every audit report populated with "violations" that simply are not. --Rusty
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.javaserverfaces.incompleteValidationMethod.comment=Not currently doing JavaServer Faces development. --Rusty 2007/05/09
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.audit.closeInFinally.comment=If you're not closing them in a finally block, how do you know they're for sure going to be closed (or at least closed in a timely manner)? --Rusty\r\n\r\nThis code has turned out to be way to restrictive when it comes to creating I/0 Stream resource pools, so we'll turn it off pending a request to Instantiations to add named class exemptions on the parameters page. --Rusty 01/10/06
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.audit.stringLiterals.comment=Turning all internationalization rules on. Some, if not many, of them will be unncessary on the server side code, and some, if not many, will impose unnecessary difficulty on server side programmers. However, this will be an internationalized application, and for each idiom prevented by these rules there is an alternative way to achieve the same effect. We can also ease up on some of them as experience permits. --Rusty
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.audit.constantConditionalExpression.severity=0
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.audit.overridingNonAbstractMethod.enabled=true
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.audit.disallowArrayInitializers.severity=0
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.audit.avoidStringBufferInstantiationWithChar.comment=Seems like a good rule. --Rusty 2008/5/5
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.audit.reusableImmutables.comment=Clearly. --Rusty
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.analysis.audit.rule.effectivejava.constructorsOnlyInvokeFinalMethods.comment=Non-final methods can be overridden by subclasses, and thus be dependent on fields of the subclass (or the super class), which have not yet been set when the non-final method is invoked on the subclass from the superclass constructor. Yes, maybe you're good enough to always avoid this possibility, but that's not always true. --Rusty\r\n\r\nThis rule is not working with the rule that does not allow you to call a method final if its in a final class\!\!\! We want both to be on, and this is the one that needs to change. So we've turned it off for now and asked Instantiations to teach it that all methods of a final class are automatically final\!\!\! --Rusty\r\n\r\nInstantiations fixed this rule. --Rusty (8/17/05)\r\n\r\nViolations of this rule are often simply fixed by declaring the class itself final, as most classes should be anyway. --Rusty (8/29/05)
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.audit.toStringMethodUsage.enabled=true
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.analysis.audit.rule.effectivejava.obeyEqualsContract.obeyGeneralContractOfEquals.enabled=true
