        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.audit.nestedSynchronizedCalls.comment=Clearly too restrictive. --Jason 2/4/2009.
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.analysis.dateAndTimeUsage.comment=Turning all internationalization rules on. Some, if not many, of them will be unncessary on the server side code, and some, if not many, will impose unnecessary difficulty on server side programmers. However, this will be an internationalized application, and for each idiom prevented by these rules there is an alternative way to achieve the same effect. We can also ease up on some of them as experience permits. --Rusty
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.audit.emptyMethod.comment=You may need a no-op impl of an instance of a template method design pattern, or to impl it later, that's why the exceptions on the parameter page are checked. --Rusty
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.analysis.audit.rule.effectivejava.overrideCloneJudiciously.comment=Don't use Java's clone mechanism. (See Effective Java) --Rusty
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.audit.useBufferedIO.comment=Right, yeah like that's always the way to do it--and what about when you implement your own buffer class? Not\! --Rusty
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.audit.unnecessaryFinalMethod.autoResolutionEnabled=false
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.audit.nonProtectedConstructorInAbstractType.comment=Clearly. --Rusty
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.spring.referencedClassNotDefined.enabled=true
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.audit.failInvokedInCatch.comment=If you catch an exception in a Junit test, then just put Assert.fail() or Assert.fail( e ), you've accomplished absolutely nothing that JUnit wouldn't have done for you if you'd not caught the exception at all. However, if you catch an exception in a JUnit test to put Assert.fail( "blah blah should not have happend blah blah" ), well, now you've done something truly useful, so we'll leave this rule off and show people over time that only the last one is acceptable, else just don't catch the exception at all. Thanks. --Rusty (10/20/05)
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.audit.largeNumberOfSwitchStatementCases.comment=Yep. --Rusty
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.audit.oneStatementPerLine.severity=2
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.audit.transientFieldInNonSerializable.comment=True, well give it a try. --Rusty 01/03/06
        com.instantiations.assist.eclipse.audit.lineLength.comment=100 charaters max per line, absolutely, including white space and end of line comments. --Rusty\r\n\r\nCeratian javadoc tags are execpted from this rule, as they contian hyperlinks which neither javadoc nor Doxygen parse correctly if they're broken across two lines. --Rusty (8/29/05)
